STEMDIFF :: Convert 4D-STEM data to powder diffractogram¶

  • Sample: TbF3 nanocrystals
  • Input data: 4D-STEM datafiles = data from SEM with pixelated STEM detector
  • Final output: 2D-powder diffraction pattern
  • Local source and backup: D:\DATA_SH\STEMDIFF\X_TESTING\2TBF3
In [1]:
# Import modules
import stemdiff.detectors, stemdiff.gvars
import stemdiff.io, stemdiff.dbase, stemdiff.psf, stemdiff.sum

1. Initialize¶

  • Objective: to define source data and parameters of diffraction images.
    • Source data = just technical parameters: detector type, location of the datafiles.
    • Diffraction images = characteristics from the previous step = seeing the datafiles.
In [2]:
# (1) Define source data
SDATA = stemdiff.gvars.SourceData(
    detector  = stemdiff.detectors.TimePix(),
    data_dir  = r'./DATA',
    filenames = r'*.dat')
In [3]:
# (2) Set parameters of diffraction images
DIFFIMAGES = stemdiff.gvars.DiffImages(
    imgsize=125, psfsize=130,
    ctype=2, csquare=20, cintensity=0.8,
    peak_height=100, peak_dist=9)

2. Database of all files¶

  • Objective: to create a database of all files (= datafiles) and calculate their basic characteristics:
    • DatafileName = name of datafile (relative to DATAFILES.data_dir)
    • Xcenter,Ycenter = intensity center of the datafile = primary beam position
    • MaxInt = maximum detected intensity
    • Peaks = number of detected peaks
    • S = Shannon entropy of given datafile/image

3. Analyze the database¶

  • Objective: to check quality of the data and decide about further processing, namely:
    • How to select datafiles with strong diffractions for summation?
    • How to calculate/estimate PSF for deconvolution?
In [6]:
# Re-read the database
# (in case the database calculation was skipped intentionally
df1 = stemdiff.dbase.read_database('dbase_all.zip')

Conclusions from the database analysis¶

  • Homogeneous bacgkround (no overflows, not too high MaxInt)
  • Crystals/agglomerates bigger than Au standard (MaxInt -> 3000).
  • Stable primary beam (no significant shift).
  • Weak, but logical correlation between number-of-peaks and entropy.
  • Dataset suitable for PSF-deconvolution Type1.

4.3. Calculate PSF¶

In [19]:
# Save the calculated PSF (in NumPy format)

# Show the calculated PSF

ax[0].imshow(np.where(sum_all<icut, sum_all, icut), cmap='viridis')
ax[1].imshow(np.where(sum_f  <icut, sum_f  , icut), cmap='viridis')

    ax[i].axis('off')
ax[0].set_title('All files')
ax[1].set_title('Filtered files')
ax[2].set_title('Filtered + deconvoluted files')
fig.tight_layout()
fig.savefig('sums_final.png', dpi=300)

# Conclusions:
# 1) STEMDIFF converted 4D-STEM data to 2D-powder diffractograms.
# 2) The 2D-powder diffractograms are saved in current directory as PNG images.
# 3) These images/diffractograms can be processed easily
#    with any suitable program for powder diffraction patterns;
#    we recommend EDIFF (a sister program of STEMDIFF).
